Houston and his wife Margaret Lea relied on slaves to perform household, agricultural, carpentry, blacksmithing, and other duties for the family. Eliza, who came with Margaret into Houston's family, was critical to running the household and raising the children. She stayed with the daughters of Sam and Margaret until she died in 1898. The multi-skilled Joshua was important to meeting the needs of the family. Houston often hired his slaves out for money and allowed them to keep a portion of the money for themselves. When Houston died, Joshua offered to give money to Margaret to help support her children.
Until they were emancipated, Houston's slaves did not control where and how they were employed. There were limits to how they could spend their free time. They had little power to make decisions for themselves and their children.
There is a question about whether Houston made a pejorative comment about Mexicans in an 1835 speech to the Texas volunteer army at Refugio. One second hand source makes this claim;<ref>{{cite book |last1=De León |first1=Arnoldo |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BJkGwn6H14IC |title=They Called Them Greasers: Anglo Attitudes toward Mexicans in Texas, 1821–1900 |date=January 1, 1983 |publisher=University of Texas Press |isbn=978-0292780545 |edition=1 |page=7 |access-date=August 24, 2020}}</ref> however, subsequent research casts doubt on the source and concludes that the disparaging comment is unlikely to have occurred.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Crisp |first1=James E. |title=Sleuthing the Alamo: Davy Crockett's Last Stand and Other Mysteries of the Texas Revolution (New Narratives in American History) |date=February 24, 2005 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0195163506 |edition=1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Analysis of Sleuthing the Alamo - 980 Words | Bartleby |url=https://www.bartleby.com/essay/Analysis-Of-Sleuthing-The-Alamo-F3ZQLVNHZSR}}</ref>

Ultimate Frisbee (sometimes called Ultimate) is a competitive non-contact [[team sport|team]] [[sport]]. The object of the game is to score points by passing the disc to a team member in the opposing team's end zone. Players may not move about the field while holding the disc. Catching is done with one hand or both hands on the rim or with hands simultaneously on the top and bottom, sometimes referred to as a clap-catch. When catching with one hand on the rim, paying attention to hand placement is essential, so that you catch on the correct side of the disc, depending on the direction in which the disc is spinning. One side will tend to spin out of your hand, while the other side will spin into your hand, making for a more secure catch. Many players avoid this problem by catching with both hands when possible. The most popular throws used in a game of ultimate are Flying disc techniques, backhand, sidearm/forehand, hammer, and scoober. Being a deep threat, with multiple throwing techniques and the ability to pass the disc before the defense has had a chance to reset, is always optimal. Some players use a throw and catch [[Flying disc freestyle|freestyle]] practice to help improve their ultimate handling skills.<ref>{{cite web|title=Freestyle the Ultimate Edge|date=25 August 2014 |url=http://www.ultimaterob.com/2014/08/25/freestyle-the-ultimate-edge/|access-date=November 13, 2015}}</ref> The game was invented in 1968 as an evening pastime by Jared Kass.

Topic chosen: The Starry Night panting
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Starry_Night
The biggest reason why I chose this article is because I’m really into painting, and one of my latest projects was taking some techniques used in the starry night painting in my own work. So I used the assignment to learn more about Vincent Van Gogh, the very famous Dutch painter. Another reason why I chose a specific article was due to the fact that it looked very organized and detailed as well as easy to understand wording.
Lead section
The leading section included a well-thought-out introduction sentence that gets straight to the point of what the rest of the article is about improvises basic and specific information about the painting. The article also talks about the creator, Vincent Van Gogh, as well as how the starry night was painted using oil paints on a canvas. The measurements of the painting, when it was created, and where the pain resides are also included. All the information provided the reader to have a summary before getting more in-depth, helping individuals better understand the later context in the article.

Content
When reading the article, I was never confused about what it was originally about because it constantly addresses during night painting, and it’s creator. The article discussed the history, interpretations, opinions individuals have, and specific analysis of the painting. The starry night article never seem to be of topic ones and always provided the necessary information to better understand the concept. Overall, I think the article was very well thought out and clear, from start to end.

Tone and Balance
Throughout the whole article, I could understand what the writer was trying to get across. It was not so advanced that I could get confused when reading; the article kept a very neutral tone throughout the whole article. I also enjoyed how the story night article shared multiple opinions from society on the painting another aspect of the article that I noticed was how the writer did well on avoiding, including their personal opinions, values or beliefs. Allowing the reader to come up with their own conclusions on what the painting represents.

Sources and References
Throughout the whole reading, there were InTEXT citations that letter to specific articles or research. The reference page was very organized and easy to look up. Any specific citations included in the article. All references related to the topic.

Organization and writing quality
Organization and writing qualities throughout the article was very obvious. The individual who wrote about the star night, painting sound passionate, and well informed based on the explanations and details expressed throughout the whole article.
Images and Media
The article included about 10 different images of the same artist. All the images were cited correctly, and each had a description underneath. These images helped the points made in the article and allowed the reader to better understand the paintings and the artists art style.

Metropolitan [[Leontius, Metropolitan of Belgrade|Leontius]] invited Hadži-Ruvim to Belgrade and asked him of the state of the people, to which he answered that "no words could describe the discontent and suffering", and advised the Metropolitan that the two cross into Austria, as the people planned an uprising against the Dahije.{{sfn|Novaković|1904|p=52}} The Metropolitan then informed the Dahije of their discussion, and the Dahije arrested Hadži-Ruvim and brought him to Kučuk-Alija on {{OldStyleDateNY|9 February|28 January}}, then tortured him to death the next day.{{sfn|Novaković|1904|pp=52-55}} Karađorđe was attacked by Uzun-Mehmed once again, it is believed on {{OldStyleDateNY|12 February|31 January}}, but Karađorđe managed to kill two or more of the attackers and fled into the woods, according to several accounts.<ref>{{harvnb|Vukićević|1907|pp=290-291}}, {{harvnb|Novaković|1904|pp=56-57}}</ref> Karađorđe went and met with hajduk leader [[Stanoje Glavaš]].{{sfn|Vukićević|1907|p=292}}
There are different accounts on the murder of Hadži-Ruvim: According to archpriest [[Matija Nenadović]] (the son of Aleksa), Hadži-Ruvim heard of the imprisonment of Nenadović and Birčanin and went to Belgrade Metropolitan [[Leontius, Metropolitan of Belgrade|Leontius]], who instead of harboring him, gave him up to Aganlija, whose men had Hadži-Ruvim beheaded at the Varoš Gate.{{sfn|Novaković|1904|p=52}} According to [[V. Karadžić]], Hadži-Ruvim went to Belgrade and sought to hide with his nephew [[Petar Moler]], who was the painter of Kučuk-Alija's mansions, but Kučuk-Alija sent him to Aganlija who threw in the dungeon.{{sfn|Novaković|1904|p=52}} According to Zemun archpriest Mihailo Pejić, Leontius invited Hadži-Ruvim to Belgrade and asked him of the state of the people, to which he answered that "no words could describe the discontent and suffering", and advised the Metropolitan that the two cross into Austria, as the people planned an uprising against the Dahije.{{sfn|Novaković|1904|p=52}} The Metropolitan then informed the Dahije of their discussion, and the Dahije arrested Hadži-Ruvim and brought him to Kučuk-Alija on {{OldStyleDateNY|9 February|28 January}}, then killed him the next day.{{sfn|Novaković|1904|p=52}}

Karađorđe was surrounded and attacked by Uzun-Mehmed (the second or third attempt), it is believed on {{OldStyleDateNY|12 February|31 January}}, but Karađorđe managed to kill two or more of the attackers and fled into the woods, according to several accounts.<ref>{{harvnb|Vukićević|1907|pp=290-291}}, {{harvnb|Novaković|1904|pp=56-57}}</ref> Karađorđe went and met with hajduk leader [[Stanoje Glavaš]].{{sfn|Vukićević|1907|p=292}}


In early February (the end of January according to Old Calendar) Fočić stayed at Šabac then secretly and quickly returned to Belgrade by boat where he and his associates discussed how to calm down the people after the murders.{{sfn|Gavrilović|1904|p=21}} The archpriest of Zemun, Pejić, wrote a letter to metropolitan [[Stefan Stratimirović]] some time between {{OldStyleDateNY|11 February|30 January}} and {{OldStyleDateNY|15 February|3 February}} saying "these days revenge was done on Serbs, which the Janissaries long wanted".{{sfn|Vukićević|1907|p=279}} By {{OldStyleDateNY|16 February|4 February}}, 72 severed heads had been brought to Belgrade.{{sfn|Novaković|1904|p=54}}
